passages.text: Deutsche Bank Research
More flats, fewer fences

History - and evidence from Germany - suggests Australia's housing target will be more achievable if construction tilts significantly in favour of attached dwellings (apartments) rather than stand- alone houses. In other words, Australia needs more flats, fewer fences...

There was an interesting detail in Australia's construction work done figures released for Q2. The real value of residential work done crept higher in the quarter, and is now at its highest level since June 2019. At first, this is good news for the Government's ambitious housing target of delivering 1.2mn new dwellings over 5 years. That is because in June 2019, 54,000 dwellings were completed. If that pace of completion were sustained every quarter for five years, it would deliver just under 1.1mn dwellings. Still not quite there, but a lot closer to target than the 45,000 dwellings completed in Q1- 25, a run- rate of only 900,000 over five years.
If (real) residential investment is running at the same level as in 2019, why are there fewer dwellings? Figure 1 illustrates the problem.
Figure 1: Dwelling expenditure is delivering fewer dwellings than it did in 2019...
Source: Deutsche Bank Research, ABS
Phil Odonaghoe Economist +61- 2- 8258- 1606

The chart shows, unsurprisingly, that there is a strong correlation between the value of dwelling construction work done (i.e. the 'cost of work') and the number of dwellings completed (the 'end result'). But the correlation has weakened in recent years. In 2019, we calculate that every \(1bn\) in residential construction expenditure translated into \(\sim 2,200\) dwellings brought to completion. In 2025, that same \(1bn\) is 'only' delivering \(\sim 1,910\) dwellings. Note that this is not an inflation story - as noted above the dollars here are measured in real, inflation adjusted terms.

Falling productivity is very likely part of the problem. But the main driver is the type of dwellings being built. In 2019, 82 apartments were being built for every 100 stand- alone houses. Today, that ratio has dropped to just 55 apartments for every 100 houses. Put simply, houses cost more than apartments. And right now, Australia is building more houses and fewer apartments (Figure 2).
Figure 2: ... because relatively fewer apartments are being built compared to stand-alone houses
Source: Deutsche Bank Research, ABG

Lessons from Germany? In an excellent series of notes (here and here), our German base of colleague Jochen Moebert has taken a deep dive into Germany's housing construction industry. One notable parallel with Australia is lacklustre productivity. Germany's may even be worse - productivity in residential construction has been in structural decline since reunification. But Jochen is upbeat about the future. Indeed, he expects a boom in German dwelling construction underpinned by aggressive industry consolidation and massive technological renewal via digitalization, robotics and industrial construction that looks set to deliver huge productivity gains through prefabricated construction. But he also concludes that fewer detached houses would be built in Germany in the future, and that a recent trend towards larger buildings with smaller apartments is likely to persist.
Australia could be set to follow a similar path. And if the Government has any chance of achieving its housing target, it might need to do so in a hurry.

Macroeconomic fluctuations often account for most of the risks associated with exposures to instruments that promise to pay fixed or variable interest rates. For an investor who is long fixed- rate instruments (thus receiving these cash flows), increases in interest rates naturally lift the discount factors applied to the expected cash flows and thus cause a loss. The longer the maturity of a certain cash flow and the higher the move in the discount factor, the higher will be the loss. Upside surprises in inflation, fiscal funding needs, and FX depreciation rates are among the most common adverse macroeconomic shocks to receivers. But counterparty exposure, issuer creditworthiness, client segmentation, regulation (including changes in assets holding limits for different types of investors), changes in tax policies, currency convertibility (which may constrain currency conversion, repatriation of profits and/or liquidation of positions), and settlement issues related to local clearing houses are also important risk factors. The sensitivity of fixed- income instruments to macroeconomic shocks may be mitigated by indexing the contracted cash flows to inflation, to FX depreciation, or to specified interest rates - these are common in emerging markets. The index fixings may - by construction - lag or mis- measure the actual move in the underlying variables they are intended to track. The choice of the proper fixing (or metric) is particularly important in swaps markets, where floating coupon rates (i.e., coupons indexed to a typically short- dated interest rate reference index) are exchanged for fixed coupons. Funding in a currency that differs from the currency in which coupons are denominated carries FX risk. Options on swaps (swaptions) the risks typical to options in addition to the risks related to rates movements.
